        <tr class='athing comtr ' id='14336005'><td>
            <table border='0'>  <tr>    <td class='ind'><img src="s.gif" height="1" width="40"></td><td valign="top" class="votelinks"><center><a id='up_14336005' href='vote?id=14336005&amp;how=up&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D14334455'><div class='votearrow' title='upvote'></div></a></center></td><td class="default"><div style="margin-top:2px; margin-bottom:-10px;"><span class="comhead">
          <a href="user?id=oren_thrall" class="hnuser">oren_thrall</a> <span class="age"><a href="item?id=14336005">5 hours ago</a></span> <span id="unv_14336005"></span><span class="par"></span> <a class="togg" n="6" href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="return toggle(event, 14336005)"></a>          <span class='storyon'></span>
                  </span></div><br><div class="comment">
                  <span class="c00">I think we have yet to see the worst of it for now. But make no mistake, huge sections of jobs are going to evaporate if not by 2019, then in the decade thereafter.<p>Not just elevator operators and dirigible pilots. A massive chunk of economic activity is going to look silly in a decade. Pretty much everything regarded as a summer job for high school teenagers is game, and that leaves a considerable number of normal, employable adults out in the cold too.<p>Magazines are pretty much already dead, and everything that went with them shrank. Music and movies have imploded hard enough to show signs of serious stress. Shops, department stores and big box retail are off balance, and will fall over before 2030.<p>It&#x27;s going to be pretty rough. Think about your first job, and the summer jobs your high school classmates had. Will your kids hold the same jobs? I doubt it.<span>
              </span><div class='reply'>        <p><font size="1">
