              <tr class='athing comtr ' id='14335925'><td>
            <table border='0'>  <tr>    <td class='ind'><img src="s.gif" height="1" width="0"></td><td valign="top" class="votelinks"><center><a id='up_14335925' href='vote?id=14335925&amp;how=up&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D14334455'><div class='votearrow' title='upvote'></div></a></center></td><td class="default"><div style="margin-top:2px; margin-bottom:-10px;"><span class="comhead">
          <a href="user?id=gumby" class="hnuser">gumby</a> <span class="age"><a href="item?id=14335925">5 hours ago</a></span> <span id="unv_14335925"></span><span class="par"></span> <a class="togg" n="21" href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="return toggle(event, 14335925)"></a>          <span class='storyon'></span>
                  </span></div><br><div class="comment">
                  <span class="c00">Debating whether the number of jobs will actually go down or not is irrelevant.<p>The fact is on the human lifetime timescale, jobs go away (farming from 1900-1940; various factory jobs in the late 1980s, coal mining 1970s-2000s etc).  People with decades in these jobs may not be able to move into equivalent (in renumeration &amp; status) replacement jobs as their skills are likely not transferable.<p>Thus to the tractor manufacturer in her 50s it is irrelevant whether there is high demand for experienced web designers or not.  Perhaps her kid can go into the job, but she very likely can&#x27;t.  This is part of the reason for the demand for low-skill (and low paying) jobs.<p>So either way we have to plan for rolling mass unemployment.  The only question is the shape of the derivative.<span>
              </span><div class='reply'>        <p><font size="1">
                      <u><a href="reply?id=14335925&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D14334455%2314335925">reply</a></u>
                  </font>
      </div></td></tr>
